<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<section xml:id="division_and_gcd" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Polynomials of a Single Variable</title>
  <subsection xml:id="rings_and_fields">
    <title>Constructing Rings and Fields</title>
    <p>
      Below are some basic examples of how to use some of the fields and rings available to you in Sage.
      Most of our computations will happen over <m>\Q</m>, but Sage implements all the sets <m>\N</m>, <m>\Z</m>, <m>\Q</m>, <m>\R</m>, and <m>\C</m>, which are accessed by doubling the letter, as below.
    </p>
    <sage>
      <input>
	print(NN)
	print(ZZ)
	print(QQ)
	print(RR)
	print(CC)
	print(QQbar)
      </input>
    </sage>
    <p>
      Both <c>RR</c> and <c>CC</c> using 53 bit precision, so working over either field is often quite messy.
      Unless your polynomial has transcendental coefficients (<eg/> <m>\pi</m>, <m>e</m>, etc.), the algebraic closure of <m>\Q</m>, <c>QQbar</c>, will do everything you might want from <c>RR</c> or <c>CC</c> with fewer decimals.
    </p>
    <sage>
      <input>
	print(QQbar)
	R.&lt;x> = RR[]
	print(x^2 + 1)
	print(factor(x^2 + 1))
	R.&lt;x> = CC[]
	print(x^2 + 1)
	print(factor(x^2 + 1))
	R.&lt;x> = QQbar[]
	print(x^2+1)
	print(factor(x^2 + 1))
      </input>
    </sage>
    
    <p>
      If you know a some Field/Galois theory, Sage is also capable of constructing and working over number fields (<ie/> fields <m>K</m> with <m>\Q \subseteq K \subseteq \bar{\Q}</m>).
      As a simple example, we can adjoin the sixth roots of unity<mdash/><ie/> the complex solutions to <m>x^6 - 1</m> to the field <m>Q</m> using the <c>NumberField</c> constructor.
      Note that you need at least two different variables here.
      We use <c>x</c> to specify the variable for the defining polynomial and <c>zeta</c> for the primitive sixth root of unity.
    </p>
    <sage>
      <input>
	R.&lt;x> = QQ[]
	K.&lt;zeta> = NumberField(x^2 + x + 1)
	S.&lt;X> = K[]
	print(K.galois_group())
	print(S)
	print(zeta^6)
      </input>
    </sage>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Polynomial Rings</title>
    <p>
      We can form polynomial rings using the construction <c>Name.&lt;var_1, ..., var_n> = Field[]</c>, where <c>Field</c> is some field from Sage and <c>Name</c> is a name of your choosing, <eg/> <m>R</m> (for ring).
    </p>
    <sage>
      <input>
	R0.&lt;x> = ZZ[]
	print(R0)
	R1.&lt;x> = QQ[]
	print(R1)
	R2.&lt;x> = RR[]
	print(R2)
	R3.&lt;x> = CC[]
	print(R3)
	R4.&lt;x,y,z> = QQ[]
	print(R4)
      </input>
    </sage>
    <p>
      If for some reason you need to work over a number field, you'll need to either unbind the variable <c>x</c> or add in a third variable to get polynomials over the number field.
      For example, we can see that adjoing any primitive sixth root of unity, the polynomial <m>x^6 - 1</m> splits completely:
    </p>
    <sage>
      <input>
	R.&lt;x> = QQ[]
	K.&lt;zeta> = NumberField(x^2 + x + 1)
	S.&lt;X> = K[]
	print(factor(x^6 - 1)) #Factorization over Q
	print(factor(X^6 - 1)) # Factorization over K
      </input>
    </sage>
    <p>
      Notice that we can ask for a factorization over <m>\bar{\Q}</m> with less labor, but the roots become more complicated.
      This is one particular advantage to working over the number field instead of the algebraic closure.
    </p>
    <sage>
      <input>
	R.&lt;x> = QQbar[]
	print(factor(x^6 - 1)) #Factorization over QQbar
      </input>
    </sage>
    <example>
      <p>
      </p>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>The Division Algorithm</title>
    <p>
      For univariate polynomial rings, Sage implements the division algorithm through the function <c>quo_rem</c>.
    </p>
    <sage>
      <input>
	R.&lt;x> = QQ[]
	f = x^3 + 2*x^2 + x + 1
	g = 2*x + 1
	q,r = f.quo_rem(g)
	print(q)
	print(r)
	print(f == g*q + r)
	f.quo_rem(g)
      </input>
    </sage>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>The Euclidean Algorithm</title>
    <p>
      Sage implements the Euclidean algorithm through the function <c>gcd</c>.
      This function accepts a pair of input values or a list of input values.
    </p>
    <sage>
      <input>
	R.&lt;x> = QQ[]
	f = x^4 - 1
	g = x^6 - 1
	h = x^2 + 2*x + 1
	print(gcd(f,g))
	print(gcd([f,g]))
	print(gcd([f,g,h]))
      </input>
    </sage>
  </subsection>
</section>
